snippet.textDisplay:
Saw a video of you letting someone with disabilities box you and you made her day. She loves ya like no other and a huge fan of yours. You have a heart of gold man! A real champ!
I love boxing and when I was 17 I was in Martial Arts and was always told I should take up boxing cause I'm fast on my feet, stamina was great and I had fast hands and hard punches with great combo's. They said I should take up boxing instead. I was 6 foot 155 pounds and fit. Problem is I ignored the advice didn't take it serious at all and wasted the years in my prime. Then I became mentally disabled not long after that and gave up on all my dreams cause of battling the depression from bipolar, social phobia, severe public anxiety, mood swings like no other and severe panic attacks that always shoots my blood pressure well over 280 over 180 with a pulse of 200 and have to be sent to the ER by ambulance cause they freak out saying that I risk a stroke or heart attack with that blood pressure spike. They give me shots of something in a IV and watch me close and release me when it lowers. I'm on blood pressure and anxiety meds now. I hate dealing with these mental issues that has stolen my freedom to be around people and took my dreams of being a pro boxer, singer or race car driver. I have talents in all those but boxing I dream and think about every day and is my favorite. My social phobia around crowds of people that makes me panic won't work in those career fields with my blood pressure issues and panic attacks. I was so active well into my 20's and then just got too depressed and locked myself away from everyone and stayed in my house where ever it was that I lived over the years. Not a day goes by where I don't think what I could've been in boxing. I was good and was fast and had a good jaw and could take hits. Everyday I put headphones on with some music I'd love as my intro and will box around the house and just imagine coming out to that intro song and the fans cheering me on and going out there and becoming a champion in my weight class. I can see it every day and know I could've done it I saw it and felt it and could've been great but mental issues sidelined my dreams just like physical disablities sideline others from their dreams. I'm 6 foot and 210 pounds now and need to start working out again but I have to be careful cause of my blood pressure. I'm almost 40 coming around in some more years. what I'd give to get back in decent shape and stand in the ring and face a real champ for a few rounds. I may just shock people with how fast I really am with boxing. Never lost a fight in my whole life when fighting bully's in school and later in life as a adult, thats the honest truth. Knocked many people cold out, was suspended many times for that even though I was defending myself or taking up for others and they never challenged me or picked on me or others after that. I was good at basketball to and had tons of black friends and none could beat me one on one. Was eventually nicknamed SLICK_T by my black friends growing up. I miss those days before my mental issues and depression crap came to be. Mentally on disability now and my stamina is going away. Use to be able the run for hours without hardly breaking a sweat and now I get winded just going up stairs a few times. I just stop and say wtf to myself. Getting older sucks and battling mental issues sucks right along with it. Anyways, congrats Joshua on winning your title back and Joshua is my birth name to lol. Take care man!

snippet.textDisplay:
Why the dislikes some ask... well the most likely reasons I could think would be


1. He talks much about his fans, he could have fought in the UK for those fans to see him yet he shagged off to Saudi instead.


2. Saudi is.... well you can go find out about Saudi and how having anything to do with there is bad news but he put the value of money about all else. I get that though, at the end of the day these guys are in for the money and if they can get more, then get more. Popularity and fans are fleeting, you're big news today, tomorrow nobody gives a shhh so get what you can while your in the limelight and at the top of the tree.


3. He was basically Wladimir Klitshcko for this fight. Jab and grab, run away and drop in a big bang here and there but never follow it up with any bad intentions. Again, I get that, if AJ loses this rematch where does he go? He had to win it so he did what he needed to do to get the job done but it wasn't what some would have considered a proper way to right the wrongs of the first fight and make a statement like a champion should.


Don't forget, Andy humiliated AJ in the first fight, no other words for it he made AJ look like a stupid over hyped muppet with no heart and no answer to a short little fat Mexican that landed some shots on him. He put AJ on his backside 4 or 5 times, had him bumbling around the ring and the ref had to stop it. So the answer most fans would have hoped for would have been for AJ to put on a show of power and skill and knock out a less fit and even fatter version of Andy in spectacular fashion... but he didn't... he just tipped and tapped and hugged and ran away, got the win.


He also STILL took some big shots from Andy from round 8-9(can't remember the exact rounds) and he takes big shots in general if the other guy he's boxing can bang so I've seen nothing in his game to suggest that if he was to fight Wilder, who AJ is a superior boxer too(and a lot of guys Wilder fights tbh!) that AJ can go 12 rounds without getting flashed by one of those lighting fast rights of Wilder and even though I'm sure AJ would be ahead on the score cards and would have dominated the fight, if you don't put Wilder away, he gonna getcha! at some point, he gonna getcha!! But I'd love to see that fight personally, let's see.
